    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so it basically says if i make a mistake, i'm on the hook for everything? are there any specific ways people usually get caught in these kinds of things? like things that might not be super obvious at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, technically, this clause allows the Disclosing Party to seek recovery for nearly any loss, including poorly discovered damages, even if the Disclosing Party was partly at fault for giving misleading information. People often get caught on unintentional negligence regarding facts, such as failing to notice changes in a client's business operations during due diligence, or by misinterpreting legal precedents they were supposed to research. Another common trap occurs when clauses are interpreted broadly by courts to include costs from unrelated third-party disputes that the Recipient simply couldn't have foreseen. Given these risks, your firm would typically want to negotiate to limit the liability to direct, foreseeable losses or only cover \"willful misconduct\" if that is reasonable for your industry.",
